kony83:

European Countries with 10–15 Year Salary Mortgage Affordability

1. Portugal (outside Lisbon & Porto)
House price to income ratio: ~7–10 in rural/coastal areas.

2. Greece
Why: Property prices fell dramatically post-crisis and are still recovering.
Affordable regions: Inland cities (Larissa, Patras), islands with low tourism.


3. Poland
Average: 10–13 annual salaries in secondary cities.

4. Hungary
House price to income: ~8–12 annual salaries


5. Romania
Mortgage affordability: As low as 7–10 years in rural areas.

6. Bulgaria
Average: 8–12 years of salary in many areas.

7. Slovakia (non-Bratislava areas)
House price to income: Often around 10–12x annual salary.

8. Baltic States (Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia)
Mortgage affordability: ~10–14x salary in smaller cities.

Countries Where 20–25 Years Is Sufficient for Pension Access

&#127470;&#127481; Italy
Minimum years for pension: 20 years (contributory pension)..
Note: With 20 years, you qualify for a full contributory pension if you've
always contributed.

&#127477;&#127481; Portugal
Minimum years: 15 years of contributions for minimum pension.
Full pension: Around 40 years, but 20–25 years gets you a proportional amount.


&#127466;&#127480; Spain
Minimum: 15 years to qualify.
20–25 years: You’d get a partial pension, increasing with each additional
year.

&#127468;&#127479; Greece
Minimum: 15 years (4,500 days) for a basic pension.
20–25 years: Qualifies you for better pension terms, depending on age.

&#127467;&#127479; France
Minimum: 10 years (43 quarters) for some pension.
20–25 years: Eligible for a partial pension, depending on salary history.

&#127463;&#127468; Bulgaria
Minimum: Around 15 years of work.
25 years: Decent partial pension.

&#127469;&#127479; Croatia
Minimum: 15 years.
25 years: Partial pension available.

&#127464;&#127486; Cyprus
Minimum: 10 years of contributions.
25 years: Qualifies you for a good portion of the pension.


